Requirements

2 Linux PCs

PC1 → Server

PC2 → Client

LAN cable or same Wi-Fi network

OpenSSH installed

1️⃣ Connect Both PCs to Same Network

Connect using LAN cable or same Wi-Fi.

Check IP address on both PCs:

ip a

Example:

Server → 192.168.0.101
Client → 192.168.0.102

2️⃣ Test Network Connectivity

From Client:

ping 192.168.0.101

If ping works → network is OK.

3️⃣ Install SSH
On Server (PC1)
sudo apt update
sudo apt install openssh-server -y
sudo systemctl start ssh
sudo systemctl enable ssh

Check:

sudo systemctl status ssh
On Client (PC2)

Usually already installed, otherwise:

sudo apt install openssh-client -y
4️⃣ Create User (Server)
sudo adduser secureuser
5️⃣ Test SSH Login (Password Authentication)

From Client:

ssh secureuser@192.168.0.101

Enter password.

Remote login successful.

Exit:

exit
6️⃣ Generate SSH Key (Client)
ssh-keygen

Press Enter for all prompts.

This creates:

~/.ssh/id_rsa
~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub
7️⃣ Copy Public Key to Server
ssh-copy-id secureuser@192.168.0.101

Enter password once.

8️⃣ Test Passwordless SSH Login
ssh secureuser@192.168.0.101

Now it logs in without password.

Exit:

exit
9️⃣ Secure File Transfer Using SCP
Upload File (Client → Server)

Create file:

echo "Hello SSH SCP" > file1.txt

Transfer file:

scp file1.txt secureuser@192.168.0.101:/home/secureuser/
Download File (Server → Client)

From client:

scp secureuser@192.168.0.101:/home/secureuser/file1.txt .

. = current directory.

🔟 Verify File
ls
